    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-03-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-03-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="218"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d218">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 857.857/112</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SWG1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-03-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 24, 1917</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 6 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1959. American consular agent, Brest, reports sinking on 15th instant at 8 p.m.,
                    of Norwegian steamer <hi rend="italic">Wilfred</hi>, from Newport, England, to
                    Gibraltar with coal. He obtained signed statement of two Americans,
                        <persName>Bill Southwood</persName>, born November 5, 1895, Wayne County,
                    Ky., coal trimmer (bearer of seaman’s identification certificate), and
                        <persName>John Palmer</persName>, born June 28, 1892, Panama (sailor’s
                    papers lost, signed on as American), who state that <hi rend="italic"
                        >Wilfred</hi> did not carry troops and was not armed. German submarine was
                    seen; it allowed crew to take to boats. <hi rend="italic">Wilfred</hi> displayed
                    Norwegian flag and regular marks on both sides. Sank 20 miles from Ushant, no
                    vessel in sight. No other Americans on board. Crew reached shore next morning,
                    no casualties. Consular agent states sea was rough and weather cold; his report
                    and the signed statement follow by mail. He has been requested to obtain
                    additional information.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sharp</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
